00:00:00.090 --> 00:00:05.940 position:56%
You're watching Visiting Yellowstone

00:00:05.940 --> 00:00:11.140 position:98%
Yellowstone offers some good bicycling opportunities for visitors to explore,

00:00:11.140 --> 00:00:14.250 position:84%
but you will need to do some preparation and planning.

00:00:14.250 --> 00:00:17.300 position:91%
The majority of the park’s road system is narrow and windy

00:00:17.300 --> 00:00:19.920 position:61%
and often busy with automobile traffic.

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:22.870 position:97%
While bicycles are allowed on all of the public roads in the park,

00:00:22.870 --> 00:00:24.790
extreme caution must be used.

00:00:24.790 --> 00:00:31.400 position:98%
On roads, the same traffic laws that apply to motorized traffic apply to bikes.

00:00:31.400 --> 00:00:34.800 position:72%
Yellowstone has over 300 miles of roadway with

00:00:34.800 --> 00:00:39.550 position:75%
elevations that range from 5,300 ft to 8,860 ft.

00:00:39.550 --> 00:00:43.260 position:94%
The National Park Service recommends bicyclists wear helmets

00:00:43.260 --> 00:00:46.780 position:86%
and reflective clothing while traveling in Yellowstone.

00:00:46.780 --> 00:00:50.640 position:98%
During periods of low visibility, bikes must be equipped with a

00:00:50.640 --> 00:00:54.550 position:97%
white light in front and a red light or reflector in the rear.

00:00:54.550 --> 00:00:58.270 position:84%
Riding bicycles abreast on public roads is prohibited.

00:00:58.270 --> 00:01:02.200 position:88%
Bicycle groups traveling through the park may not exceed

00:01:02.200 --> 00:01:06.800 position:95%
15 bikes per cluster. Clusters must be at least ½ mile apart.

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:11.170 position:98%
Groups and individuals that plan on camping in Yellowstone should

00:01:11.170 --> 00:01:14.870 position:98%
make reservations before they arrive by contacting Xanterra Parks

00:01:14.870 --> 00:01:24.410 position:75%
and Resorts at 307-344-7311 or 1-866-GEYSERLAND.

00:01:24.410 --> 00:01:28.890 position:97%
All National Park Service managed campgrounds are on a first-come,

00:01:28.890 --> 00:01:32.080 position:88%
first-served basis and they often fill early in the day.

00:01:32.080 --> 00:01:35.120 position:64%
There are a limited number of hiker/biker

00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:37.760 position:70%
campsites available in most park campgrounds.

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:41.930 position:98%
One of the best times to ride on the park roads is in the spring.

00:01:41.930 --> 00:01:46.000 position:97%
There is a period, usually early April, depending on conditions,

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:49.150 position:81%
before motorized traffic is allowed in the park that

00:01:49.150 --> 00:01:52.520 position:95%
bikes are allowed to travel between West Yellowstone, Montana

00:01:52.520 --> 00:01:57.250 position:98%
and Mammoth Hot Springs. Stay alert, because administrative traffic is also

00:01:57.250 --> 00:02:02.610 position:98%
allowed during this period and wildlife, including bears, may be in the road.

00:02:02.610 --> 00:02:07.550 position:97%
If you can’t be here in April and you still plan on biking on the public roads

00:02:07.550 --> 00:02:12.380 position:98%
in the park, it is best to get out early in the day. Traffic will increase as the

00:02:12.380 --> 00:02:15.420 position:95%
day goes along. Always be prepared for changing weather while

00:02:15.420 --> 00:02:18.490 position:86%
biking in Yellowstone. It can snow anytime of the year.

00:02:18.490 --> 00:02:24.530 position:95%
Away from the public road system there are good opportunities

00:02:24.530 --> 00:02:27.910 position:86%
for bicyclists. Mountain bikes are best in these areas.

00:02:27.910 --> 00:02:32.120 position:97%
The Old Gardiner Road is a gravel road that begins just behind the

00:02:32.120 --> 00:02:36.210 position:97%
Mammoth Hot Springs Hotel and ends at the park’s North Entrance.

00:02:36.210 --> 00:02:42.250 position:98%
This is a one-way auto road, but bicycles are allowed to travel in both directions.

00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:46.850 position:98%
A short service road that is open for bicyclists and hikers can be accessed

00:02:46.850 --> 00:02:51.650 position:97%
from here. Located between Mammoth Hot Springs and Tower Junction,

00:02:51.650 --> 00:02:55.660 position:98%
Blacktail Plateau Drive is another one-way automobile road that

00:02:55.660 --> 00:02:59.010 position:73%
allows bicyclists to travel in both directions.

00:02:59.010 --> 00:03:03.340 position:98%
Use caution whether you are traveling by auto or bike in these areas.

00:03:03.340 --> 00:03:08.230 position:98%
Routes that are open to hiking and biking exclusively are limited

00:03:08.230 --> 00:03:11.300 position:77%
in Yellowstone, but there are some opportunities.

00:03:11.300 --> 00:03:15.350 position:98%
North of Mammoth, bikes are allowed on an old railroad bed that follows

00:03:15.350 --> 00:03:18.860 position:81%
the Yellowstone River just outside Gardiner, Montana

00:03:18.860 --> 00:03:21.640 position:73%
to Reese Creek at the park’s northern boundary.

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:25.820 position:97%
South of Mammoth, bicyclists can ride the old Bunsen Peak Road

00:03:25.820 --> 00:03:28.160
between Golden Gate and Joffe Lake.

00:03:28.160 --> 00:03:32.800 position:81%
Just inside the park’s West Entrance, bicyclists can

00:03:32.800 --> 00:03:35.660 position:72%
travel from the Riverside trail to Barns Road.

00:03:35.660 --> 00:03:39.050 position:91%
This trail gives access to a section of the Madison River.

00:03:39.050 --> 00:03:43.940 position:97%
A few miles north of Old Faithful, bikes are allowed on the Fountain

00:03:43.940 --> 00:03:48.530 position:98%
Freight Road. You can access this road from either end, just north of the

00:03:48.530 --> 00:03:52.380 position:94%
Lower Geyser Basin or just south of the Midway Geyser Basin.

00:03:52.380 --> 00:03:55.960 position:88%
You can park your bike and access Fairy Falls from here.

00:03:55.960 --> 00:04:00.740 position:98%
In the Upper Geyser Basin, which includes Old faithful, bikes are allowed

00:04:00.740 --> 00:04:04.950 position:97%
on the paved path between the Old faithful Lodge and Morning Glory Pool.

00:04:04.950 --> 00:04:10.410 position:98%
A short trail from Daisy Geyser to Biscuit Basin is also open to bikes.

00:04:10.410 --> 00:04:14.240 position:97%
Bikes are not allowed on the boardwalks, but there are several

00:04:14.240 --> 00:04:17.580 position:91%
bike racks where you can park your bike while you explore.

00:04:17.580 --> 00:04:22.210 position:98%
Just South of Old Faithful Village, the Lone Star Trail follows the

00:04:22.210 --> 00:04:25.570 position:88%
Firehole River to a backcountry geyser of the same name.

00:04:25.570 --> 00:04:29.400 position:97%
Check at the Old Faithful Visitor Center for information regarding

00:04:29.400 --> 00:04:33.100 position:91%
Lone Star Geyser. Bikes are not allowed beyond the geyser.

00:04:33.100 --> 00:04:38.790 position:97%
Near Lake Village, bicyclists can access Yellowstone’s Natural Bridge.

00:04:38.790 --> 00:04:41.910 position:63%
The trail begins near Bridge Bay Marina.

00:04:41.910 --> 00:04:45.730 position:98%
Bikes are also allowed on an old roadbed that runs between the Lake Hotel

00:04:45.730 --> 00:04:50.340 position:95%
and the main road. Between Canyon Village and Tower Junction,

00:04:50.340 --> 00:04:54.120 position:98%
hardy bicyclists may want to ride to the top of Mount Washburn.

00:04:54.120 --> 00:04:59.080 position:97%
Access is from theChittenden Road Trailhead and it climbs nearly 1500 feet

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:02.410 position:97%
in just over 2.5 miles. The view from Mount Washburn is spectacular.

00:05:02.410 --> 00:05:08.180 position:98%
Bikes are not allowed on the trail from Dunraven Pass to the mountain’s summit.

00:05:08.180 --> 00:05:12.290 position:98%
Near Tower Falls bikes are allowed on the Old Chittenden service road

00:05:12.290 --> 00:05:15.800 position:98%
that runs between the Tower Falls campground and the Grand Loop Road.

00:05:15.800 --> 00:05:20.080 position:97%
All other service roads and trails in the park are closed to bicycles.

00:05:20.080 --> 00:05:24.100 position:95%
Always check at a park Visitor Center before you venture out.

00:05:24.100 --> 00:05:28.960 position:97%
Park trails can close due to bear activity or other dangers at any time.

00:05:28.960 --> 00:05:33.560 position:98%
Always follow any posted closures and be alert for bear activity.

00:05:33.560 --> 00:05:38.240 position:97%
If you didn’t bring a bike, you can rent one from Xanterra Parks

00:05:38.240 --> 00:05:40.470 position:67%
and Resorts at the Old Faithful Snow Lodge,

00:05:40.470 --> 00:05:43.170 position:77%
though they must remain in the Old Faithful area.

00:05:43.170 --> 00:05:46.820 position:97%
Rentals are also available in some of the local communities; West Yellowstone,

00:05:46.820 --> 00:05:51.000 position:98%
Montana and Cooke City, Montana are the closest towns that offer bike

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:55.910 position:97%
repair shops. Check here on our website for current conditions

00:05:55.910 --> 00:05:58.610 position:86%
or email us if you can’t find what you are looking for.

00:05:58.610 --> 00:06:01.940 position:98%
When you arrive you can get a Bicycling in Yellowstone Pamphlet

00:06:01.940 --> 00:06:05.230 position:97%
from any of the park’s visitor centers. Remember you are responsible

00:06:05.230 --> 00:06:08.650 position:83%
for knowing where you are and what rules apply there.

00:06:08.650 --> 00:06:14.640 position:97%
Yellowstone is a great place to explore and we can’t wait to see you here.

